You are the **people** extractor for curator.

Source text:        {{ source_text_path | default('(missing)') }}
Container metadata: {{ container_metadata | default('(none)') }}
{% if topic is defined %}Topic: {{ topic }}{% endif %}

Identify people associated with the source:

1. **Author.** From `container_metadata` (the source's published
   byline). Always include even if the byline is just a name with
   no further info. Set `role: author`.
2. **Source-attested people.** Anyone substantively named, quoted,
   or discussed in the source body. Pick a role from:
   `guest`, `speaker`, `researcher`, `engineer`, `scholar`,
   `contributor`, `editor`, `host`. Skip casual mentions.

For each person, write a short definition (1–3 sentences) describing
who they are, drawing only on what the source says about them. If
the source says nothing beyond the name, the definition can be
empty-string or a single phrase from the byline.

You have NO access to the vault. Do not concern yourself with
duplicates or existing pages — a separate stage will reconcile your
output against the vault later.

---

## OUTPUT — WRITE HERE

Output target:

    {{ output_path }}

### 1. Initialize

    curator.sh builders init {{ output_path }} --schema people

### 2. Add each person (pick ONE variant per item)

#### Variant A — author (from container metadata)

    curator.sh builders add {{ output_path }} \
        --set people.<i>.name='<full name>' \
        --set people.<i>.role=author \
        --set people.<i>.definition='<1-3 sentences>' \
        --set people.<i>.source_quote=<verbatim-passage|null>

`source_quote` MAY be null if the author is named only in the
metadata and never appears in the source body.

#### Variant B — source-attested (named in source body)

    curator.sh builders add {{ output_path }} \
        --set people.<i>.name='<full name>' \
        --set people.<i>.role=<guest|speaker|researcher|engineer|scholar|contributor|editor|host> \
        --set people.<i>.definition='<1-3 sentences>' \
        --set people.<i>.source_quote='<verbatim passage from source>'

`source_quote` MUST be a real passage from the source body.
